			<h2>Strong Adjectives</h2>
			<p><span class="initial-letter darkorange-text">T</span>he strong form of an adjective is used
				when the adjective is linked to a noun without any demonstrative pronoun or possessive personal pronoun.
				For example, '<em>Hie sind halig ond eaþmod menn - they are holy and humble men</em>' and
				'<em>Hat ðu me heagne tor getimbrian - you, order a high tower to be built</em>'. The strong form of the
				adjective is also used in sentences with a linking verb (what we call a predicative adjective): so '<em>se cyning is eald</em>' would take the strong
				form of the adjective because it follows a linking verb rather than appearing between the demonstrative pronoun and the noun.
			</p>
