							<p>The endings of plural adjectives with long stems differ from those with short stems.
								Short stemmed plural masculine adjectives end in '<strong>e</strong>', neuter in
								'<strong>u</strong>', and feminine in '<strong>a</strong>'. Long stemmed plural
								masculine and neuter adjectives end in '<strong>e</strong>', and feminine in
								'<strong>a</strong>'. However, be aware the nominative and accusative plural
								ending starts to normalise to just '<strong>e</strong>' in later Old English.
